{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775859874286,"sessionID":"ses_28682202effebETHvvgChqKWBH","part":{"id":"prt_d797f3647001rDnFXAJD6oIr6O","messageID":"msg_d797f2288001sTF1dVnrzzKn2o","sessionID":"ses_28682202effebETHvvgChqKWBH","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_3e71ab9896764c65810cd0a7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-019/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-019/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Spec: AR-019 — CLI Binary Entry (4 Binaries)\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: This delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing CLI binary entry points in `cmd`. Four binaries must be created: `agentd`, `picod`, `router`, and `workloadmanager`.\n6: \n7: ## Base Specifications\n8: \n9: - **AR**: AR-019\n10: - **Module**: `cmd`\n11: - **Language**: Go\n12: - **Size**: M\n13: - **Dependencies**: client-go library (`pkg/client`) for Kubernetes client integration\n14: \n15: ---\n16: \n17: ## Background\n18: \n19: The agentcube project comprises multiple independent services that need to be deployed and run as separate processes in a Kubernetes cluster. Currently, only `agentd` and `picod` have binary entry points. The `router` and `workloadmanager` packages exist in `pkg/` but lack standalone binary entry points in `cmd/`.\n20: \n21: ---\n22: \n23: ## Requirements\n24: \n25: ### AR-019-001: Router Binary Entry Point\n26: \n27: The router binary SHALL provide an HTTP routing service entry point with configurable flags.\n28: \n29: #### Scenario: AR-019-001-A — Router binary builds successfully\n30: \n31: - **GIVEN** the `cmd/router` directory contains a `main.go` file\n32: - **WHEN** `go build -o bin/router ./cmd/router` is executed\n33: - **THEN** the build completes without errors\n34: - **AND** a `router` binary is created in the `bin/` directory\n35: \n36: #### Scenario: AR-019-001-B — Router binary displays help\n37: \n38: - **GIVEN** the router binary has been built successfully\n39: - **WHEN** `./bin/router -h` is executed\n40: - **THEN** help text is displayed including available flags:\n41:   - `--listen` (default: \":8080\")\n42:   - `--backend-timeout`\n43:   - `--health-check-interval`\n44:   - `--rate-limit`\n45:   - `--auth-enabled`\n46: \n47: #### Scenario: AR-019-001-C — Router binary starts with default configuration\n48: \n49: - **GIVEN** the router binary is built and no flags are provided\n50: - **WHEN** `./bin/router` is executed\n51: - **THEN** the router starts listening on \":8080\"\n52: - **AND** responds to `/healthz` endpoint with HTTP 200\n53: \n54: #### Scenario: AR-019-001-D — Router binary handles SIGTERM gracefully\n55: \n56: - **GIVEN** the router binary is running\n57: - **WHEN** SIGTERM is sent to the process\n58: - **THEN** the server stops accepting new connections\n59: - **AND** existing connections are allowed to complete\n60: - **AND** the process exits with code 0\n61: \n62: ---\n63: \n64: ### AR-019-002: Workload Manager Binary Entry Point\n65: \n66: The workload manager binary SHALL provide a workload orchestration service entry point with Kubernetes client integration.\n67: \n68: #### Scenario: AR-019-002-A — Workload manager binary builds successfully\n69: \n70: - **GIVEN** the `cmd/workloadmanager` directory contains a `main.go` file\n71: - **WHEN** `go build -o bin/workloadmanager ./cmd/workloadmanager` is executed\n72: - **THEN** the build completes without errors\n73: - **AND** a `workloadmanager` binary is created in the `bin/` directory\n74: \n75: #### Scenario: AR-019-002-B — Workload manager binary displays help\n76: \n77: - **GIVEN** the workload manager binary has been built successfully\n78: - **WHEN** `./bin/workloadmanager -h` is executed\n79: - **THEN** help text is displayed including available flags:\n80:   - `--port` (default: 8080)\n81:   - `--kubeconfig` (optional)\n82:   - `--shutdown-timeout`\n83:   - `--enable-metrics`\n84: \n85: #### Scenario: AR-019-002-C — Workload manager binary starts with default configuration\n86: \n87: - **GIVEN** the workload manager binary is built and no flags are provided\n88: - **WHEN** `./bin/workloadmanager` is executed\n89: - **THEN** the server starts listening on port 8080\n90: - **AND** responds to `/healthz` endpoint with HTTP 200\n91: - **AND** responds to `/readyz` endpoint with HTTP 200\n92: \n93: #### Scenario: AR-019-002-D — Workload manager binary handles SIGINT gracefully\n94: \n95: - **GIVEN** the workload manager binary is running\n96: - **WHEN** SIGINT (Ctrl+C) is sent to the process\n97: - **THEN** the server stops accepting new requests\n98: - **AND** the HTTP server shuts down within the configured timeout\n99: - **AND** the process exits with code 0\n100: \n101: #### Scenario: AR-019-002-E — Workload manager initializes Kubernetes client\n102: \n103: - **GIVEN** a valid kubeconfig exists at `~/.kube/config`\n104: - **WHEN** the workload manager starts\n105: - **THEN** a Kubernetes clientset is created using `clientcmd.BuildConfigFromFlags`\n106: - **AND** informers are initialized for `runtime/v1alpha1` API group\n107: \n108: ---\n109: \n110: ### AR-019-003: Agentd Binary Entry Point\n111: \n112: The agentd binary SHALL provide a Kubernetes controller for idle cleanup.\n113: \n114: #### Scenario: AR-019-003-A — Agentd binary builds successfully\n115: \n116: - **GIVEN** the `cmd/agentd` directory contains a `main.go` file\n117: - **WHEN** `go build -o bin/agentd ./cmd/agentd` is executed\n118: - **THEN** the build completes without errors\n119: - **AND** an `agentd` binary is created in the `bin/` directory\n120: \n121: #### Scenario: AR-019-003-B — Agentd binary displays help\n122: \n123: - **GIVEN** the agentd binary has been built successfully\n124: - **WHEN** `./bin/agentd -h` is executed\n125: - **THEN** help text is displayed showing available flags\n126: \n127: #### Scenario: AR-019-003-C — Agentd binary handles signals gracefully\n128: \n129: - **GIVEN** the agentd binary is running\n130: - **WHEN** SIGTERM is sent to the process\n131: - **THEN** the controller manager stops\n132: - **AND** the process exits gracefully\n133: \n134: ---\n135: \n136: ### AR-019-004: Picod Binary Entry Point\n137: \n138: The picod binary SHALL provide a PicoD execution server entry point.\n139: \n140: #### Scenario: AR-019-004-A — Picod binary builds successfully\n141: \n142: - **GIVEN** the `cmd/picod` directory contains a `main.go` file\n143: - **WHEN** `go build -o bin/picod ./cmd/picod` is executed\n144: - **THEN** the build completes without errors\n145: - **AND** a `picod` binary is created in the `bin/` directory\n146: \n147: #### Scenario: AR-019-004-B — Picod binary displays help\n148: \n149: - **GIVEN** the picod binary has been built successfully\n150: - **WHEN** `./bin/picod -h` is executed\n151: - **THEN** help text is displayed including available flags:\n152:   - `--port` (default: 8080)\n153:   - `--workspace`\n154: \n155: #### Scenario: AR-019-004-C — Picod binary handles signals gracefully\n156: \n157: - **GIVEN** the picod binary is running\n158: - **WHEN** SIGINT is sent to the process\n159: - **THEN** the server stops\n160: - **AND** the process exits gracefully\n161: \n162: ---\n163: \n164: ### AR-019-005: Consistent Flag Parsing Pattern\n165: \n166: All binaries SHALL follow a consistent flag parsing pattern.\n167: \n168: #### Scenario: AR-019-005-A — All binaries use consistent flag initialization\n169: \n170: - **GIVEN** any of the four binaries\n171: - **WHEN** the binary starts\n172: - **THEN** `klog.InitFlags(nil)` is called\n173: - **AND** flags are parsed using `flag.Parse()`\n174: \n175: #### Scenario: AR-019-005-B — All binaries support --kubeconfig flag\n176: \n177: - **GIVEN** the router or workloadmanager binary\n178: - **WHEN** `--help` is displayed\n179: - **THEN** a `--kubeconfig` flag is listed for Kubernetes configuration\n180: \n181: ---\n182: \n183: ## Architecture Notes\n184: \n185: ### Directory Structure\n186: \n187: ```\n188: cmd/\n189: ├── agentd/\n190: │   └── main.go           # Binary entry point (existing)\n191: ├── picod/\n192: │   └── main.go           # Binary entry point (existing)\n193: ├── router/\n194: │   └── main.go           # New binary entry point\n195: └── workloadmanager/\n196:     └── main.go           # New binary entry point\n197: ```\n198: \n199: ### Key Functions\n200: \n201: | Binary | Package | Key Function | Description |\n202: |--------|---------|--------------|-------------|\n203: | `agentd` | `cmd/agentd` | `main()` | Uses controller-runtime manager |\n204: | `picod` | `cmd/picod` | `main()` | Creates `picod.Server` |\n205: | `router` | `pkg/router` | `RunWithSignal(*Config)` | HTTP router with middleware |\n206: | `workloadmanager` | `pkg/workloadmanager` | `NewServer(*Config, WorkloadManager)` | Workload orchestration API |\n207: \n208: ### Configuration\n209: \n210: | Binary | Config Type | Default Port |\n211: |--------|-------------|--------------|\n212: | `agentd` | Manager options | 0 (healthz only) |\n213: | `picod` | `picod.Config` | 8080 |\n214: | `router` | `router.Config` | 8080 |\n215: | `workloadmanager` | `workloadmanager.Config` | 8080 |\n216: \n217: ### Environment Variables\n218: \n219: | Variable | Used By | Description |\n220: |----------|---------|-------------|\n221: | KUBECONFIG | router, workloadmanager | Path to kubeconfig file |\n222: \n223: ---\n224: \n225: ## References\n226: \n227: - Module: `cmd`\n228: - Base: `pkg/client` - Generated Kubernetes client for `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1`\n229: - Related: `pkg/router` - Router implementation\n230: - Related: `pkg/workloadmanager` - Workload manager implementation\n231: - Related: AR-018 - Agentd idle cleanup controller\n232: - Related: AR-012 - Workload Manager service\n\n(End of file - total 232 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Delta Spec: AR-019 — CLI Binary Entry (4 Binaries)\n\n## Overview\n\nThis delta-spec defines acceptance scenarios for implementing CLI binary entry points in `cmd`. Four binaries must be created: `agentd`, `picod`, `router`, and `workloadmanager`.\n\n## Base Specifications\n\n- **AR**: AR-019\n- **Module**: `cmd`\n- **Language**: Go\n- **Size**: M\n- **Dependencies**: client-go library (`pkg/client`) for Kubernetes client integration\n\n---\n\n## Background\n\nThe agentcube project comprises multiple independent services that need to be deployed and run as separate processes in a Kubernetes cluster. Currently, only `agentd` and `picod` have binary entry points. The `router` and `workloadmanager` packages exist in `pkg/` but lack standalone binary entry points in `cmd/`.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-MiniMax-M2.5_20260410T163134Z/changes/AR-019/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775859874265,"end":1775859874282}}}}
